<BlogLayout
  title="Why 3D3D Runs Prusa | And What That Actually Means"
  description="We chose Prusa for our entire fleet. Not because it's trendy. Because when you're running parts for boats and drag cars, you need machines that just work."
  datePublished="2025-04-15"
  author="Ken"
>
  <h2>The Short Answer</h2>

  <p>
    People ask me all the time why I didn't go with a Bambu or a Creality or one of the dozen Chinese machines that cost half as much. Fair question. Here's the honest answer: I've been burned too many times by cheap tools.
  </p>

  <p>
    I spent ten years as a mechanic. I've owned the $40 socket set from the parts store. I've watched those sockets round off on the third bolt. Then I bought Snap-on, and those same sockets lasted the rest of my career. Prusa is Snap-on for 3D printing. It costs more up front and saves you money every single day after that.
  </p>

  <h2>Open Source Matters More Than You Think</h2>

  <p>
    Prusa machines run on open-source firmware. That means I can see the code. I can modify it. If something breaks, I can fix it myself without waiting for a company in Shenzhen to push an update that may or may not address my issue.
  </p>

  <p>
    When you're running a fabrication business, not a hobby, a <em>business</em>, you can't afford to be locked into a proprietary ecosystem that decides what filament you're allowed to use or what slicer settings you're allowed to change. Prusa doesn't do that. They publish their designs. They encourage you to tinker. That philosophy lines up with how I build things.
  </p>

  <h2>Reliability Is the Whole Game</h2>

  <p>
    I've run Prusa machines for thousands of hours. MK3S+, MK4, CORE One. These machines just print. They heat up, they home, they lay down filament, and they do it again and again without drama.
  </p>

  <p>
    That might sound boring. It is boring. Boring is exactly what you want when a client needs a marine bracket by Thursday and you've got three other jobs in the queue. I don't have time to recalibrate, re-level, or re-flash firmware because some update bricked my z-offset. Prusa machines respect your time.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>First-layer calibration:</strong> Set it once, forget it for months.</li>
    <li><strong>Filament sensor:</strong> Actually works. Pauses the print, lets you reload, carries on.</li>
    <li><strong>Power panic recovery:</strong> Power goes out in the shop? Print resumes where it left off.</li>
    <li><strong>Input shaping:</strong> On the MK4 and CORE One, prints are faster without sacrificing quality.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Slicer Is Underrated</h2>

  <p>
    PrusaSlicer is genuinely excellent software. It's free. It handles multi-material. The support generation is the best in the industry. And because it's open-source, the community contributes improvements constantly.
  </p>

  <p>
    I've used Cura, I've used OrcaSlicer, I've tried them all. PrusaSlicer gives me the most consistent results with the least fiddling. For production work, that's everything.
  </p>

  <h2>What It Means for 3D3D Clients</h2>

  <p>
    When you order a part from us, it's coming off a Prusa. That means consistent dimensional accuracy, clean surfaces, and reliable layer adhesion. It means the part you get matches the part we prototyped. Every time.
  </p>

  <p>
    We're not chasing the cheapest machine or the flashiest marketing. We're running tools that work, made by a company that shares our values: open, transparent, built to last. That's the whole pitch. It's not complicated.
  </p>

  <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    Cheap printers print cheap parts. You get what you pay for in this industry, same as any other. I chose Prusa because I've spent my whole career learning that lesson the hard way with tools, and I'm done learning it. These machines earn their keep every day. That's why they're the backbone of 3D3D.
  </p>
</BlogLayout>
